{
  "text": "The sampling design of the African American Health (AAH) cohort has been described elsewhere. [CITATION_1] Briefly, AAH is a population-based cohort study of 998 noninstitutionalized African Americans recruited in 2000 to 2001 using multistage probability sampling. All participants lived in one of two geographic sampling strata: either a poor, inner-city area (St. Louis, MO, USA) or more heterogeneous suburbs just northwest of the City of St. Louis. Interviewers (two thirds of whom were African American) with extensive study-specific training screened households for eligibility criteria, which involved self-reported Black or African American race, birth date from 1936 through 1950, and Mini-Mental State Examination scores \u226516. This age group was selected to examine the progression of subclinical disability to more overt disability. Participants were paid volunteers. Sampling proportions were set to recruit approximately equal numbers of participants from both areas (sampling strata).",
